In 1950, Kerouac began studying Buddhism<ref name="tyger">{{cite web|last=Ginsberg|first=Allen|title=The Vomit of a Mad Tyger|url=http://www.lionsroar.com/the-vomit-of-a-mad-tyger/|publisher=Lion's Roar|date=2015-04-03|access-date=2015-04-03|archive-date=2021-12-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211216231151/https://www.lionsroar.com/the-vomit-of-a-mad-tyger/|dead-url=no}}</ref> and shared what he learned from [[Zen_in_the_United_States#Dwight_Goddard|Dwight Goddard's]] ''Buddhist Bible'' with Ginsberg.<ref name="tyger" /> Ginsberg first heard about the [[Four_Noble_Truths|Four Noble Truths]] and such sutras as the [[Diamond_Sutra|Diamond Sutra]] at this time.<ref name="tyger" />

Ginsberg's spiritual journey began early on with his spontaneous visions, and continued with an early trip to India with [[Gary_Snyder|Gary Snyder]].<ref name="tyger" /> Snyder had previously spent time in [[Kyoto|Kyoto]] to study at the First Zen Institute at [[Daitoku-ji|Daitoku-ji Monastery]].<ref name="tyger" /> At one point, Snyder chanted the [[Prajnaparamita|Prajnaparamita]], which in Ginsberg's words "blew my mind."<ref name="tyger" /> His interest piqued, Ginsberg traveled to meet [[14th_Dalai_Lama|the Dalai Lama]] as well as the [[Karmapa|Karmapa]] at Rumtek Monastery.<ref name="tyger" /> Continuing on his journey, Ginsberg met [[Dudjom_Jigdral_Yeshe_Dorje|Dudjom Rinpoche]] in [[Kalimpong|Kalimpong]], who taught him: "If you see something horrible, don't cling to it, and if you see something beautiful, don't cling to it."<ref name="tyger" />

After returning to the United States, a chance encounter on a New York City street with [[Chögyam_Trungpa|Chögyam Trungpa]] [[Rinpoche|Rinpoche]] (they both tried to catch the same cab),<ref>{{cite book|last=Fields|first=Rick|title=How the Swans Came to the Lake: A Narrative History of Buddhism in America|url=https://archive.org/details/howswanscametola0000fiel|year=1992|page=[https://archive.org/details/howswanscametola0000fiel/page/n311 311]|publisher=Shambhala Publications|isbn=978-0-87773-631-8}}</ref> a [[Kagyu|Kagyu]] and [[Nyingma|Nyingma]] [[Tibetan_Buddhism|Tibetan Buddhist]] master, led to Trungpa becoming his friend and lifelong teacher.<ref name="tyger" /> Ginsberg helped Trungpa and New York poet [[Anne_Waldman|Anne Waldman]] in founding the Jack Kerouac School of Disembodied Poetics at [[Naropa_University|Naropa University]] in [[Boulder,_Colorado|Boulder, Colorado]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beatdom.com/pages/archives/issue1.html#buddhism|title="The Beats and Travel" by David S. Wills}}</ref>

Ginsberg was also involved with [[Vaishnavism|Krishnaism]]. He had started incorporating chanting the [[Hare_Krishna_(mantra)|Hare Krishna mantra]] into his religious practice in the mid-1960s. After learning that [[A._C._Bhaktivedanta_Swami_Prabhupada|A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada]], the founder of the [[International_Society_for_Krishna_Consciousness|Hare Krishna]] movement in the Western world had rented a store front in New York, he befriended him, visiting him often and suggesting publishers for his books, and a fruitful relationship began. This relationship is documented by [[Satsvarupa_dasa_Goswami|Satsvarupa dasa Goswami]] in his biographical account ''Srila Prabhupada Lilamrta''. Ginsberg donated money, materials, and his reputation to help the Swami establish the first temple, and toured with him to promote his cause.<ref>
